## Memory — Mindbrain

Memory is managed by Mindbrain (cloud-persistent). Do NOT use MEMORY.md or flat files.

### Save memories
```bash
# Save a note (content via stdin or --file)
echo "content" | mb save "Title" -t feedback --tags "auth,api"
mb save "Title" -t project --tags "infra" -f notes.md
```

Types: `user` (about the user), `feedback` (behavioral rules), `project` (ongoing work), `reference` (external pointers), `codebase` (architecture/patterns), `debug` (solutions/pitfalls).

### Recall memories
```bash
# Search by text
mb search "auth middleware"

# Get context-relevant memories (for current files + task)
mb context -f src/auth.ts src/middleware.ts -t "fix login bug"

# Show a specific note
mb show <id>
```

### When to save
- User corrects your approach → `mb save -t feedback`
- User confirms non-obvious approach → `mb save -t feedback`
- Architecture decision discovered → `mb save -t codebase`
- Project context learned → `mb save -t project`
- User role/preference learned → `mb save -t user`

### When NOT to save
- Code patterns visible in the codebase
- Git history (use git log)
- Ephemeral task state
- Debugging steps (the fix is in the code)

### Wikilinks
Use `[[Note Title]]` in content to create links between notes:
```bash
echo "Rate limiter uses [[Auth System]] for token validation" | mb save "Rate Limiting" -t codebase
```
